All of these conversations sound extremely odd, and I wasn't really sure what it meant for the responses to sound "good," but they were all consistent with the original statements' topics.

I think it would be important to have the instructions available throughout the whole experiment. In the first part, I was doubting that I was answering correctly because I thought all the sentences were very awkward and not something that would be said in real life.. but was pretty sure they were grammatically correct. I kept questioning myself on how I should answer.

The second half of the survey was challenging. What is used to determined if it is "good" or not? If it makes sense? If it is something someone would actually say? The "responses" were not something anyone would actually say in a real conversation, in my opinion.
